<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-904-600  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 904 600.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Nov 20 1989 v6 n46 p21(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Extra font capabilities expected in upgrade to HP printerlanguage. (Hewlett-Packard)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bernard, Diane.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>HP is planning on upgrading its LaserJet printer language.andO;Sources say Printer Control Language 5 (PCL 5) will be availablein Feb 1990 and will support Intellifont outline font technologyand an enhanced version of HP Graphics Language for plotters.andP;  PCL5 will also include expanded support for third party fonts throughthe use of a tag-metric file.andP;  The file makes add-in third partyfonts compatible with LaserJets and could make third party printerdrivers obsolete.andP;  No pricing or specification information isbeing released by HP yet, but a spokesperson hints that theLaserJet II with PCL 5 will be priced competitively.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Hewlett-Packard Co. (product enhancement).andO;Ticker:    HWP.andO;Product:   HP LaserJet II (Computer printer) (product enhancement).andO;Topic:     Laser printersEnhancementsFonts.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Diane BernardandM;Hewlett-Packard Co.'s (HP's) next-generation LaserJet printer  language isstill in the wings, but  industry sources say the new language will hit thestreets with  performance improvements and  a price point that will make it well worth the wait.andM;Last year, the PC printer giant  promised to bring out an upgrade  to thecurrent LaserJet printer  command language (PCL) controller, called PCL 4, bythis fall.andP;  Sources close to the firm, however, say that PCL 5 will make its debut in February.andM;As promised, PCL 5 will provide support for Agfa Compu graphic Division'sIntellifont outline font technology as well as an  enhanced version of theHewlett- Packard Graphics Language for plotter output, sources said.andM;In addition, HP will expand  font support in the forthcoming  printerlanguage by adding a special file that supports additional  third-partyfonts, sources said.andM;To provide support for such  fonts, HP plans to ship diskettes  that containa tag-font metric file, or auto-font file.andP;  Users can  load the diskettesinto PC memory to format third-party add-in  printer fonts for compatibility with a new LaserJet featuring  PCL 5, according to the sources.andM;If included in PCL 5 as expected, the auto-font file will give usersautomatic access to a wide  range of fonts.andP;  In addition, software developerswill no longer  have to write printer drivers for  their programs thatinclude third-party fonts, said Mark Zachmann, president of Z-Soft Corp. inMarietta, Ga.andM;Many developers anticipate the new printer language's font- handling andgraphics enhancements will cause a stir in the market if HP announces theproduct  on a printer priced at the current  LaserJet II's $2,695 price tag.andM;Although HP officials would not comment on pricing or specific features ofthe new printer language, Bill McGlynn, marketing  manager of HP's printerdivision in Boise, Idaho, addressed the need to bring out new printer technology at competitive pricing.andM;&quot;We'll continue to build PCL up  as costs for the technology continue todrop,&quot; he said.andM;Hewlett-Packard recently held  a third-party developers conference to rallysupport for the new  language and to ensure that it will  be announced withwidespread  software support.andP;  Officials from  several software firms,including  WordPerfect Corp. and Z-Soft, said they plan to support PCL 5 upon announcement or shortly thereafter.andO;</TEXT></DOC>